1 Introduction

A geospatial risk model is a regression model, whose dependent variable is the occurrence of discrete events like crime, fires, successful sales calls, locations of donut shops, etc.36 Predictions from these models are interpreted as the forecasted risk/opportunity of that event occurring here.

For crime, the hypothesis is that crime risk is a function of exposure to a series of geospatial risk and protective factors, such as blight or recreation centers, respectively. The assumption is that as exposure to risk factors increases, so does crime risk.

In this assignment, we selected three factors to predict the likelihood of narcotics crime. It has some bias

1.2 A map of your outcome of interest in point form

For crime bias, the hypothesis is that crime risk is a function of exposure to a series of geospatial risk and protective factors, such as blight or recreation centers, respectively. The assumption is that as exposure to risk factors increases, so does crime risk.

I have categorized the causes of bias in several ways: observed bias: Some sources of bias may be due to certain factors that go unobserved. For example, for rodent alarm behavior, some may not have observed them.

reported bias:Some other sources of bias may come from whether people want to report. There are some incidents, such as fires, where people are more likely to call the police, but some, such as noise reports, where people have varying levels of tolerance for these things and dont necessarily report them. This is when reporting bias arises.

## using {sf} to create the grid
## Note the `.[chicagoBoundary] %>% ` line. This is needed to clip the grid to our data
fishnet <- 
  st_make_grid(chicagoBoundary,
               cellsize = 500, 
               square = TRUE) %>%
  .[chicagoBoundary] %>%            # fast way to select intersecting polygons
  st_sf() %>%
  mutate(uniqueID = 1:n())

Aggregate points to the fishnet

## add a value of 1 to each crime, sum them with aggregate
crime_net <-

abandonCars: I continued to follow this parameter from the lab because abandoned vehicles often represent the degree of desolation of a place and are related to our predicted narcotics crime.
rodentBaiting:I included this variable because places where rodents roam tend to represent poor sanitation and discipline. I included this variable because places where rodents roam tend to represent poorer sanitation and discipline. But this factor is subject to some bias.
shotspotterAlerts: ShotSpotter is a gunshot detection system designed to automatically determine the location of potential outdoor gunfire. ShotSpotter audio sensors are placed in several CPD districts throughout the city (specific districts are noted below).

3.4 Modeling and CV

Here is small multiple map of model errors by random k-fold and spatial cross validation. We can see that the mean error is bigger in the place with more narcotics.

final_net <- final_net %>% 
  mutate(abandoned.isSig = 
           ifelse(local_morans[,5] <= 0.001, 1, 0)) %>%
  mutate(abandoned.isSig.dist = 
           nn_function(st_c(st_coid(final_net)),
                       st_c(st_coid(filter(final_net, 
                                           abandoned.isSig == 1))), 
                       k = 1))
reg.vars <- c("Abandoned_Cars.nn", "shotspotterAlerts.nn",   
              "rodentBaiting.nn","abandoned.isSig", "abandoned.isSig.dist")

reg.ss.vars <- c("Abandoned_Cars.nn", "shotspotterAlerts.nn",   
              "rodentBaiting.nn","abandoned.isSig", "abandoned.isSig.dist")
CRV <- function(dataset, id, dependentVariable, indVariables) {
  
  allPredictions <- data.frame()
  cvID_list <- unique(dataset[[id]])
  
  for (i in cvID_list) {
    
    thisFold <- i
    cat("This hold out fold is", thisFold, "\n")
    
    fold.train <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] != thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
      dplyr::select(id, geometry, indVariables, dependentVariable)
    fold.test  <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] == thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
      dplyr::select(id, geometry, indVariables, dependentVariable)
    
    regression <-
      glm(countNarcotics ~ ., family = "poisson", 
          data = fold.train %>% 
            dplyr::select(-geometry, -id))
    
    thisPrediction <- 
      mutate(fold.test, Prediction = predict(regression, fold.test, type = "response"))
    
    allPredictions <-
      rbind(allPredictions, thisPrediction)
    
  }
  return(st_sf(allPredictions))
}
reg.cv <- CRV(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",                           
  dependentVariable = "countNarcotics",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countNarcotics, Prediction, geometry)

reg.ss.cv <- CRV(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countNarcotics",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countNarcotics, Prediction, geometry)
  
reg.spatialCV <- CRV(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",
  dependentVariable = "countNarcotics",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countNarcotics, Prediction, geometry)

reg.ss.spatialCV <- CRV(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",
  dependentVariable = "countNarcotics",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countNarcotics, Prediction, geometry)
reg.summary <- 
  rbind(
    mutate(reg.cv,           Error = Prediction - countNarcotics,
                             Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Just Risk Factors"),
                             
    mutate(reg.ss.cv,        Error = Prediction - countNarcotics,
                             Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Spatial Process"),
    
    mutate(reg.spatialCV,    Error = Prediction - countNarcotics,
                             Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV: Just Risk Factors"),
                             
    mutate(reg.ss.spatialCV, Error = Prediction - countNarcotics,
                             Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV: Spatial Process")) %>%
    st_sf() 
error_by_reg_and_fold <- 
  reg.summary %>%
    group_by(Regression, cvID) %>% 
    summarize(Mean_Error = mean(Prediction - countNarcotics, na.rm = T),
              MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T),
              SD_MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T)) %>%
  ungroup()

error_by_reg_and_fold %>%
  ggplot(aes(MAE)) + 
    geom_histogram(bins = 30, colour="black", fill = "#FDE725FF") +
    facet_wrap(~Regression) +  
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0) + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 8, by = 1)) + 
    labs(title="Distribution of MAE", subtitle = "k-fold cross validation vs. LOGO-CV",
         x="Mean Absolute Error", y="Count") +
    plotTheme()

From the map, we can find that the MAE is larger in the central western part, about 30. Here is also the space that is clustered as we found in the Local Morans I-related test.

  st_as_sf(coords = c("x", "y"), crs = st_crs(final_net)) %>%
  aggregate(., final_net, mean) 
kde_breaks <- classIntervals(burg_KDE_sum$value, 
                             n = 5, "fisher")
burg_KDE_sf <- burg_KDE_sum %>%
  mutate(label = "Kernel Density",
         Risk_Category = classInt::findCols(kde_breaks),
         Risk_Category = case_when(
           Risk_Category == 5 ~ "5th",
           Risk_Category == 4 ~ "4th",
           Risk_Category == 3 ~ "3rd",
           Risk_Category == 2 ~ "2nd",
           Risk_Category == 1 ~ "1st")) %>%
  cbind(
    aggregate(
      dplyr::select(narcotics18) %>% mutate(narcoCount = 1), ., sum) %>%
    mutate(narcoCount = replace_na(narcoCount, 0))) %>%
  dplyr::select(label, Risk_Category, narcoCount)
ml_breaks <- classIntervals(reg.ss.spatialCV$Prediction, 
                             n = 5, "fisher")
burg_risk_sf <-
  reg.ss.spatialCV %>%
  mutate(label = "Risk Predictions",
         Risk_Category =classInt::findCols(ml_breaks),
         Risk_Category = case_when(
           Risk_Category == 5 ~ "5th",
           Risk_Category == 4 ~ "4th",
           Risk_Category == 3 ~ "3rd",
           Risk_Category == 2 ~ "2nd",
           Risk_Category == 1 ~ "1st")) %>%
  cbind(
    aggregate(

  dplyr::select(label,Risk_Category,narcoCount)

Is this what we see? High risk categories with few 2018 observed narcotics may suggest latent risk or a poorly fit model. This ambiguity is why accuracy for geospatial risk models is tough to judge. We can also find that in south Chicago, the prediction shows some features of the highest level of narcotics. Nevertheless, more features/feature engineering would be helpful.

4.2 The bar plot making this comparison.

As is shown in this plot, the code block below calculates the rate of 2018 narcotics points by risk category and model type. A well fit model should show that the risk predictions capture a greater share of 2018 narcotics in the highest risk category relative to the Kernel density. However, in our plot, in the 5th level the predictions are less than kernel density, which means that the model may not be good enough. However, for the 4th level, the model shows a good prediction.

rbind(burg_KDE_sf, burg_risk_sf) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -label, -Risk_Category) %>%
  group_by(label, Risk_Category) %>%
  summarize(Countnarco = sum(Value)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(label) %>%
  mutate(Pcnt_of_test_set_crimes = Countnarco / sum(Countnarco)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(Risk_Category,Pcnt_of_test_set_crimes)) +
      geom_bar(aes(fill=label), position="dodge", stat="identity") +
      scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE, name = "Model") +
      labs(title = "Risk prediction vs. Kernel density, 2018 narcotics",
           y = "% of Test Set Burglaries (per model)",
           x = "Risk Category") +
  theme_bw() +
      theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 0.5))

5 Conclusion

For this model, I will not recommend my algorithm be put into production. First, and most importantly, I think the selection of these factors is inherently biased. As stated above, this bias may come from peoples tolerance of these factors and whether they are observed. In addition to this, the selection of the factors themselves is subjective and in a sense targets communities of color, which can exacerbate this bias if judged by the results of this model.

Second, there are some problems with the model itself. Because not enough feature engineering factors are added, the model itself is an incomplete model with a poor fit, much smaller than the realistic kernel density in the highest level of crime prediction.

Therefore, from both aspects, I do not recommend this model.
